summary.seg: An early-13th-century English manuscript containing Latin glosses on the Old Testament from Genesis to II Maccabees by Stephen Langton (c. 1150-1228), the scholar and former Archbishop of Canterbury usually credited with dividing the Vulgate bible into chapters. This manuscript was made during Langton’s lifetime, and in his 2016 catalogue of the Peterhouse manuscripts, R.M. Thomson suggests that some notes present at the end of the manuscript in a 12th-century scholastic script may be Langton’s autograph.

The history and provenance of the manuscript are rather obscure. Both MSS 112 and its companion MS 119 part IV, another volume of Langton commentaries in the same hand, are present in the catalogue of Peterhouse books dated 24 December, 1418, but nothing further is known. Still, the manuscript is thoroughly marked by the use of centuries of scholars: underlining and marginal annotation is present in multiple hands spanning the 13-15th centuries, and Thomson identifies two potential culprits – that of John Warkworth, a frequent annotator of Peterhouse books, and William Dyngley.

msItem.title: Tract on the Seven Deadly Sins

supportDesc.foliation: Quires numbered at the end at foot, and foliation in modern pencil on the first leaf of each quire, upper right-hand corner, recto, but it does not entirely correspond to the collation laid out by Thomson in his 2016 catalogue. For example, folio i (per Thomson) is marked as “1.”

collation.p: The manuscript consists of 19 quires + two bifolia as follows:

layout.p: Ruled in crayon and written in two columns of between 66-83 lines.

handNote.p: Written in an early Nothern textualis script. According to Thomson, it is the same hand as that found in Peterhouse MS 119 part IV.

decoNote.p: Folios 1r and 2r have red or blue initials flourished in the opposite colour.
Very occasional plain red or blue initials.
Red chapter numbers in the margins.

additions.p: The manuscript is heavily annotated in several hands of the 13th to 15th centuries, one of the latter being frequently found in other Peterhouse manuscripts as well. Thomson notes that it may be the hand of John Warkworth (1425-500), onetime Master of Peterhouse, while another may be William Dyngley, Peterhouse scholar and bibliophile. Thomson further suggests that the extracts for sermons found at ff. 189r-190v may be in the hand of Stephen Langton himself.
Two tables of contents have been added on f. ir, one for this volume and one for its companion, presumably Peterhouse MS 119 part IV.
On the front pastedown: a thoroughly erased inscription at the top; “James 112” in modern pencil; inscription in ink below describing contents.

bindingDesc.p: Standard College binding, 18th century; the cover is a reused College lease dated 1765; medieval parchment endpapers. The front pastedown (and subsequent few leaves) has several rust marks in a vertical line down the centre, “probably from rivets fastening skin to the boards of a half binding” (Thomson, 62).

provenance.p: Ex dono of Stockton, John John Stockton (d. 1361) , fellow of Peterhouse and rector of Brington, Northamptonshire present on f. iv.

name.persName: John de Runham, Master of Michaelhouse, 1351-1354

recordHist.source: This records draws on R.M. Thomson, A Descriptive Catalogue of the Medieval Manuscripts in the Library of Peterhouse, Cambridge, as well as M.R. James, A Descriptive Catalogue of the Manuscripts in the library of Peterhouse, Cambridge.
